  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Ellicott's Commentary for English Readers",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(21) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "And upon a set day . . .",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "—Josephus (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Ant.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " xix. 8, § 2) gives an account of the incident that follows substantially agreeing with that here recorded. The scene was the theatre at Cæsarea, which had been built by Herod the Great. Agrippa was celebrating games in honour of the Emperor Claudius, who had succeeded Caligula in A.D. 41, possibly in honour of his return from Britain in A.D. 44. He was arrayed in a robe of silver tissue, such as Caligula had been wont to wear at banquets and games in Rome, which glittered with a dazzling brightness under the rays of the morning sun. His courtiers, taking up the Roman fashion of showing honour to kings and emperors, hailed him as a god, and prayed him, as such, to be propitious to them. The king did not repress the flattery, which fell on the ears of all Jewish by-standers as a fearful blasphemy. He accepted for himself the divine honours which he had dissuaded Caligula from claiming. He looked up, and saw an owl perched on a rope behind him, and recognised in it an omen of evil, fulfilling a prediction which had been made to him by a fellow-prisoner during his confinement at Rome (Jos. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Ant. xviii.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " 8). Sharp pain fell on him, and in five days he died.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Comparing St. Luke’s narrative with this, it seems probable that the delegates from Tyre and Sidon were among those who raised the cry, “Be thou propitious to us,” and that their friend Blastus, knowing the weak point in Herod’s character, had instructed them that this was the way to obtain his favour. We feel, as we read the narrative, the contrast between St. Peter’s refusal even of Cornelius’s attitude of homage, and Agrippa’s acceptance of the profane apotheosis of the multitude.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Benson Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Acts 12:21-23",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Acts 12:21-23",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "And upon a set day ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— When shows and games were exhibited by him in honour of Claudius Cesar; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Herod, arrayed in royal apparel — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "In a garment so wrought with silver, that the rays of the rising sun, striking upon, and reflected from it, dazzled the eyes of the beholders; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "sat upon his throne ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— In a public theatre; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "and made an oration unto them",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " — Not to the Tyrian and Sidonian deputies merely, but unto all the people assembled on this grand occasion. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "And the people gave a shout, It is the voice of a god, and not of a man ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— Such profane flattery the heathen frequently paid to princes. But the commonness of a wicked custom rather increases than lessens the guilt of it. And the unhappy king, instead of expressing a just indignation at such base and impious adulation, hearkened to it with a secret pleasure. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "And immediately — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "For frequently God does not delay to vindicate his injured honour; an ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "angel of the Lord smote him",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " — Of this, other historians say nothing; so wide a difference there is between divine and human history! An angel of the Lord brought out Peter, an angel smote Herod. Men did not see the instruments in either case: these were only known to the people of God. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Because he gave not God the glory ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— Did not reject these blasphemous applauses, but willingly received them, and thus filled up the measure of his iniquities. So then vengeance tarried not. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "And he was eaten of worms ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— Or vermin, which bred in his bowels, and rendered him a most loathsome and horrible spectacle to all about him; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "he ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "gave up the ghost ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— Expired in agony and infamy, (as his grandfather, Herod the Great, had done, see on ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Matthew 2:19",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ",) and sunk as much below the common state of human nature, as his flatterers endeavoured to raise him above it! The Jewish historian, Josephus, confirms St. Luke’s account of the end of this miserable man. He tells us, that “as he did not rebuke the impious flattery addressed to him, he was immediately seized with exquisite and racking tortures in his bowels, so that he was compelled, before he left the place, to own his folly in admitting such acclamations, and upbraided those about him with the wretched condition in which they then saw their god; and being carried out of the assembly to his palace, he expired in violent agonies, the fifth day after he was taken, in the fifty-fourth year of his age, and the seventh of his reign.” ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Antiq., Acts 19:7",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "Antiq., ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Acts 19:7",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
